%text The discrete random variable $X$ can have only one of the four given values -- $0.5,1,1.5$ and $2$ Hence, $\sum P(X) = 1$, that is, % \begin{align}
k + k^2 + 2k^2 + k &= 1 \\ \implies 3k^2 + 2k - 1 &= 0 \\ \text{or } \left(3k-1 \right)\cdot (k + 1) &= 0 \\ \text{or } k &= \frac{1}{3}, -1 \end{align} %text Now, if $k = -1$, then $P(1.5) > 1$ and $P(0.5) < 0$ This makes no sense. Hence, only $k=\frac{1}{3}$ is an acceptable solution The expected value of $X = E(X)$ is simply % \begin{align}
E(X) &= \sum P(X)\cdot X \\ &= \left[\frac{1}{3}\cdot\frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{9}\cdot 1 + \frac{2}{9}\cdot\frac{3}{2} + \frac{1}{3}\cdot 2 \right] \\ &= \frac{23}{18} \end{align} %text %
